abla}_k W_{ij}^k-\overline{
abla}_j W_{ki}^k)+( rac{g^{ij}}{t}+\dot{g}^{ij})(W_{k\ell}^k W_{ij}^\ell-W_{j\ell}^k W_{ik}^\ell)	ag{5}$$ for small $t
eq 0$ . If the above is true, all we have to do now is take its limit at $t=0$ . But after seeing that $$\lim_{t	o 0}\dot{g}^{ij} ar{R}_{ij}=\dot{g}^{ij} ar{R}_{ij}=\langle\mathrm{Ric}_g,\dot{g}angle_g,	ag{6}$$ I began to hesitate about the computation because I didn't have a minus sign to compensate (6) for the formula to be derived in Exercise 1.18. Why's that? What should I do next? Thank you. Remark 1. I'm not worried about $\dot{g}^{ij}(\overline{
abla}_k W_{ij}^k-\overline{
abla}_j W_{ki}^k)$ and $\dot{g}^{ij}(W_{k\ell}^k W_{ij}^\ell-W_{j\ell}^k W_{ik}^\ell)$ in (5) because these terms contribute nothing as indicated by the hint. Remark 2. The hint says that in any orthonormal frame $\{v_i\}_i$ , the double divergence of $\dot{g}$ is given by $$\mathrm{div}_g\mathrm{div}_g\dot{g}=\sum_{i,j}\dot{g}_{ij;ij},$$ which I have just checked. And in the same frame, I also checked that $$ egin{align} \Delta_g\mathrm{tr}_g\dot{g}&=\mathrm{div}_g\mathrm{grad}(g^{ij}\dot{g}_{ij})\ &=\sum_k\left(v_k(v_k(\sum_i \dot{g}_{ii}))+\sum_j v_j(\sum_i\dot{g}_{ii})\overline{\Gamma}_{kj}^kight) \end{align}$$ and that $$\langle\mathrm{Ric}_g,\dot{g}angle_g=\sum_{i,j} ar{R}_{ij}\dot{g}_{ij}.$$ These local expressions follow from a straightforward computation. The crux of my attempt really lies in the expansion of those $W$ terms. Originally, I planned on taking it by employing $$W_{ij}^k= rac{1}{2}g_t^{k\ell}\left(\overline{
abla}_i(g_t)_{\ell j}+\overline{
abla}_j(g_t)_{i\ell}-\overline{
abla}_\ell(g_t)_{ij}ight),$$ another result obtained previously (see The components $W_{ij}^k$ of the difference $W=
abla-\overline{
abla}$ between two Levi-Civita connections ), but the algebra really hurts.

